summary_points: 1. On March 19, 2025, Expeditors International named Kelly K. Blacker as its new President - Global Geographies, effective April 1, 2025.
2. Ms. Blacker joined Expeditors in 1994 and has held various management positions within the company since then, most recently serving as President, Global Products.
3.  The filing states that there are no special arrangements or conflicts of interest related to Ms. Blacker's appointment.
1. Diamondback Energy, Inc. completed a $1,200,000,000 public offering of 5.550% Senior Notes due 2035 on March 20, 2025.
2.  The Notes are senior unsecured obligations, ranking equally with existing and future senior indebtedness.
3. The Indenture contains customary terms and covenants, including limitations on incurring liens and on the sale of assets.
1. On March 20, 2025, Jeffrey Ettinger was elected to the Hormel Foods Corporation Board of Directors, joining the Governance and ad hoc CEO Search Committees.
2.  The Hormel Foundation, an unaffiliated non-profit, beneficially owns approximately 46% of Hormel Foods' outstanding common stock.
3. Mr. Ettinger's compensation will be the same as other non-employee directors, as detailed in Hormel Foods' 2025 proxy statement filed December 18, 2024.
1. JoAnn A. Reed, a member of the Audit Committee, will not stand for re-election at the 2025 Annual Meeting of Stockholders.
2.  This 8-K filing, dated March 20, 2025, reports on events that occurred on March 17, 2025.
3. The filing contains no specific future impacts or risks with associated numbers.
1. Nike, Inc.'s fiscal 2025 third-quarter revenues were $11.3 billion, a 9% decrease compared to the same period last year.
2.  Gross margin decreased by 330 basis points to 41.5%, primarily due to increased discounts, higher inventory obsolescence, product costs, and changes in channel mix.
3.  Nike repurchased 6.5 million shares in the third quarter as part of its four-year, $18 billion share repurchase program, leaving approximately $6.2 billion remaining as of February 28, 2025.
1. FedEx's cash and cash equivalents decreased by $1.4 billion between May 31, 2024, and February 28, 2025, reaching $5.1 billion.
2.  A European workforce reduction plan, announced in June 2024, will cost between $250 million and $300 million pre-tax through fiscal year 2026.
3. FedEx plans to spin off FedEx Freight by June 2026, a tax-free transaction for U.S. shareholders.

1. On March 19, 2025, Universal Health Services Inc. (UHS) replaced the existing employment agreements of Marc D. Miller (CEO) and Alan B. Miller (Executive Chairman) with new agreements, guaranteeing their compensation through 2028 and 2027 respectively,  and including a 6.7% and 4.0% salary increase for Marc and Alan respectively, compared to their 2024 salaries.

2.  Marc D. Miller's 2025 target annual bonus is 150% of his $1,500,000 base salary, while other executive officers have 2025 target bonuses ranging from 100% to 150% of their base salaries, based on a combination of corporate and divisional performance criteria for the year ending December 31, 2025.

3.  Marc D. Miller and Alan B. Miller were each awarded 28,077 and 14,213 time-based RSUs and performance-based PBRSUs respectively, on March 19, 2025, with the RSUs vesting over four years and the PBRSUs vesting based on three-year adjusted EBITDA growth against pre-established targets.
1. FedEx Corp. reported diluted EPS of $3.76 and adjusted diluted EPS of $4.51 for the fiscal quarter ending February 28, 2025, compared to $3.51 and $3.86 respectively for the same period in 2024.

2.  FedEx revised its full-year fiscal 2025 diluted EPS outlook to $15.15 to $15.75 before mark-to-market adjustments (compared to a prior forecast of $16.45 to $17.45), and $18.00 to $18.60 after excluding certain costs (compared to a prior forecast of $19.00 to $20.00).
3.  The company completed a $500 million share repurchase during the quarter, and as of February 28, 2025, had $2.6 billion remaining available for repurchases under its 2024 authorization.

1. On March 20, 2025, AES Corp completed an offering of $800,000,000 in 5.800% Senior Notes due 2032, intending to use the net proceeds to fund the purchases of its 3.300% Senior Notes due 2025 in a tender offer and for general corporate purposes.
2.  The tender offer for the 3.300% Senior Notes due 2025, which closed on March 18, 2025, resulted in 86.25% ($776,214,000) of the outstanding notes being tendered.
3. The 5.800% Senior Notes due 2032 are subject to a "make whole" redemption price before January 15, 2032, and a 101% repurchase price upon a Change of Control Triggering Event.
1. Qualcomm Inc.'s 2025 Annual Meeting on March 18, 2025, resulted in the approval of all proposals except for a shareholder proposal regarding retirement benefits.
2.  Over 700 million votes were cast in favor of Proposal 4, approving the amended and restated long-term incentive plan, which includes an increase in the share reserve by 22,950,000 shares.
3. The significant number of withhold and abstain votes for the election of directors (Proposal 1) suggests potential concerns from some shareholders regarding the board's composition or performance.
1. Micron Technology, Inc. reported fiscal Q2 2025 revenue of $8.05 billion, down from $8.71 billion in the previous quarter but up from $5.82 billion in the same period last year.
2.  Micron's data center DRAM revenue tripled year-over-year in fiscal Q2 2025, reaching a record high.
3. Micron projects record quarterly revenue in fiscal Q3 2025, driven by increasing DRAM and NAND demand across data center and consumer markets.
1. Therace M. Risch resigned from her position as Executive Vice President and Chief Information and Technology Officer, effective April 1, 2025.
2.  This filing is an 8-K Current Report, filed on March 20, 2025, concerning the departure of a director or officer.
3. No specific future impacts or risks are mentioned beyond the resignation of a key executive.
1. MPS increased its Q1 2025 revenue guidance to a range of $630.0 million to $640.0 million.
2.  Q1 2025 GAAP and non-GAAP operating expenses were revised upward due to increased stock-based compensation and other expenses.
3.  MPS's March 20, 2025 SEC filing disclosed material cybersecurity incidents.

1. Arthur J. Gallagher & Co. announced plans on March 5, 2025, to host an investor meeting on March 20, 2025, including an updated “CFO Commentary” with estimates for 2025 results and future net after-tax cash flows from clean energy investments.
2.  The 8-K filing shows that as of March 20, 2025, Arthur J. Gallagher & Co. is not an emerging growth company.
3. The CFO Commentary contains forward-looking statements, indicating potential risks associated with the accuracy of the provided financial projections.
1. CBRE Group, Inc. recast its historical financial information on March 20, 2025, to reflect a new business segment structure effective January 1, 2025.
2.  As of January 1, 2025, CBRE now reports financial results across four business segments: Advisory Services, Building Operations & Experience, Project Management, and Real Estate Investments.

3. The acquisition of the remaining equity interest in Industrious and the combination of the project management business with Turner & Townsend led to the creation of two new business segments, Building Operations & Experience and Project Management, impacting future reporting starting Q1 2025.

1. Jabil Inc. reported preliminary, unaudited second-quarter fiscal year 2025 (ended February 28, 2025) net revenue of $6.7 billion, exceeding expectations due to strong performance in specific end-markets.
2.  Compared to the same period in 2024, second-quarter 2025 U.S. GAAP operating income significantly decreased from $1.131 billion to $245 million.

3. Jabil's outlook for the third quarter of fiscal year 2025 (ending approximately May 2025) projects net revenue between $6.7 billion and $7.3 billion, with U.S. GAAP diluted earnings per share predicted to be between $1.50 and $1.99.

1. Darden Restaurants' total sales increased by 6.2% year-over-year in the third quarter of fiscal year 2025, reaching $3.2 billion, driven by acquisitions and new restaurant openings, despite a modest 0.7% increase in same-restaurant sales.
2.  Adjusted diluted net earnings per share from continuing operations for Q3 FY25 was $2.80, a 6.9% increase year-over-year, excluding $0.06 per share in Chuy's transaction and integration costs.

3. Darden Restaurants updated its full-year fiscal 2025 financial outlook to include approximately $12.1 billion in total sales and adjusted diluted net earnings per share from continuing operations of $9.45 to $9.52,  excluding approximately $47 million in pre-tax Chuy's transaction and integration costs.
1. Accenture's Q2 2025 revenue increased by 5% in USD (8.5% in local currency) compared to Q2 2024.
2.  Accenture faces material adverse effects from a data security lawsuit and a DOJ investigation into Accenture Federal Services, with undetermined costs and timing of resolution.
3. Accenture's non-current investments significantly increased to $441,720,000 as of February 28, 2025, from $334,664,000 as of August 31, 2024.
1. Accenture plc reported second-quarter fiscal 2025 revenues of $16.7 billion, a 5% increase in U.S. dollars and an 8.5% increase in local currency compared to the same period in 2024.
2.  As of March 20, 2025, Accenture narrowed its full-year fiscal 2025 revenue growth outlook to 5% to 7% in local currency,  predicting a negative 0.5% foreign exchange impact.
3.  Accenture's days sales outstanding (DSOs) increased to 48 days at February 28, 2025, from 43 days at February 29, 2024.
1. News Corp repurchased approximately US$650,499,333.65 worth of Class A and Class B shares as of March 19, 2025, under a US$1 billion stock repurchase program.
2.  On March 19, 2025, 21,283,564 Class A shares and 10,502,220 Class B shares were repurchased at prices ranging from US$14.88 to US$30.69 (Class A) and US$15.17 to US$35.25 (Class B).
3. News Corp's future share repurchases are subject to market conditions, the market price of the company's stock, and other factors, and there is no guarantee of further repurchases.

1. On March 17, 2025, Caesars Entertainment, Inc. appointed Jesse Lynn and Ted Papapostolou to its Board of Directors,  both designees of the Icahn Group,  following a Director Appointment and Nomination Agreement that includes standstill and voting commitments.

2.  The Icahn Group’s standstill restrictions on acquiring more than 5% of Caesars' outstanding common stock will remain in effect until at least 30 calendar days before the nomination deadline for the 2026 annual meeting of stockholders.

3. The agreement between Caesars and the Icahn Group requires the resignation of one or both Icahn designees from the Board if the Icahn Group's beneficial ownership falls below 10,551,100 or 5,275,550 shares of common stock, respectively (with adjustments for certain events).
1. FactSet's Q2 2025 GAAP revenues were $570.7 million, a 4.5% increase year-over-year, driven by growth from wealth and institutional buy-side clients.
2.  Organic ASV increased by $90.7 million year-over-year to $2,276.2 million (a 4.1% increase), while GAAP operating margin decreased by approximately 80 basis points year-over-year to 32.5%.

3. FactSet's updated fiscal 2025 guidance predicts organic ASV growth of $100 million to $130 million (approximately 4.4% to 5.8%), with GAAP diluted EPS expected to be in the range of $14.80 to $15.40 (down from the previous guidance of $15.10 to $15.70).

1. On March 19, 2025, Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. completed exchange transactions of approximately $213 million in 6.000% Convertible Senior Notes due 2025 for approximately 3.3 million shares of common stock and $214 million in cash.
2.  The Exchange Transactions reduced Royal Caribbean's fully diluted outstanding shares by 1.0 million shares, leaving approximately $110 million in 2025 Notes outstanding as of March 19, 2025.

3. The issued shares were part of a private placement, exempt from registration under Section 4(a)(2) of the Securities Act of 1933, relying on representations that holders are accredited and qualified institutional buyers.

1. On March 18, 2025, Celanese Corporation announced early results and an upsize of cash tender offers to purchase up to €552,082,000 of its 4.777% Senior Notes due 2026 and up to $500,000,000 of its 6.415% Senior Notes due 2027.

2.  As of the early tender time on March 18, 2025, €552,082,000 of the 2026 notes and $1,354,646,000 of the 2027 notes were validly tendered, resulting in a pro-rata acceptance of the 2027 notes at a 36.40% rate.
3. Celanese expects to settle the tendered notes on March 21, 2025.
1. Quest Diagnostics' 2024 operating income increased by 11.1% year-over-year.
2. Project Nova, a $250-$310 million IT modernization initiative, is expected to generate $150-$200 million in annual cost savings by 2031, three years ahead of schedule.
3.  Quest Diagnostics projects a 4%-5% revenue CAGR and a 7%-9% adjusted EPS CAGR beyond 2025.
1. General Mills' net sales decreased 5% year-over-year in the third quarter of fiscal 2025 (ending February 23, 2025), primarily due to decreased volume.
2.  The company completed the sale of its Canadian yogurt business for a pre-tax gain of $95.9 million and acquired NX Pet Holding, Inc. for $1.4 billion in cash during the same period.
3. The pending sale of the U.S. yogurt business, with $730.2 million in assets and $20.5 million in liabilities as of February 23, 2025, is expected to impact future financial results.
1. Best Buy's fiscal year 2025 revenue decreased by 4.4% year-over-year to $41.5 billion, accompanied by a $475 million goodwill impairment charge related to Best Buy Health.
2. Best Buy plans to close 5-10 stores in its Domestic segment in fiscal year 2026.
3.  Best Buy expects to recognize $133 million in unrecognized compensation expense over the next 1.8 years related to non-vested time-based share awards.
